## 4. Notify the regulator

For each active jurisdiction where the breach is notifiable:

### Singapore PDPA — file at https://eservice.pdpc.gov.sg/case/db

Within **3 calendar days** of assessment. Include:

- Nature of the breach (one paragraph)
- When discovered, when it occurred (or "unknown — under investigation")
- Number of affected individuals (estimate is fine if exact unknown — update later)
- Types of personal data involved
- Cause (root cause if known; "under investigation" otherwise)
- Likely harm to individuals
- Containment + remediation actions taken
- Steps individuals can take to protect themselves
- DPO contact

Save the submission receipt in the incident log.

If a SG law-enforcement agency or PDPC instructs you to delay individual notification (s26D(6)), record the instruction and pause section 5.

### Indonesia / Thailand / Malaysia

Use the relevant authority's portal and form. For **Malaysia**, file via the JPDP Personal Data Protection System within 72 hours of discovery (s12B(1)); the JPDP Guideline on Data Breach Notification (25 Feb 2025) sets the form/content. If the assessment is incomplete at H+72, submit a preliminary notification within the window and supplement later. For **Indonesia** and **Thailand**, verify the current portal and form at the time of incident.

---

## 5. Notify affected individuals

Required when significant harm is likely (and no tech-measure exception applies).

### Channels (in order of preference)

1. Email to the address on file
2. In-app banner on next launch
3. Push notification (only if email + in-app aren't reaching them)

### Template

```
Subject: Important: a security incident affecting your {{APP_NAME}} account

Hi {{first_name}},

On {{date}}, we discovered that {{one-line description of what happened}}.
We notified {{REGULATOR}} on {{date}}.

What data was involved: {{bullet list of data categories}}
What we have done: {{containment steps}}
What you should do: {{specific user actions, e.g. reset password, log out everywhere, monitor for unusual activity}}

We're sorry this happened. If you have any questions, reply to this email
and it will reach me directly.

{{DPO_NAME}}
Data Protection Officer, {{LEGAL_ENTITY}}
{{DPO_EMAIL}}
```

Save the send log (recipient count, send timestamp) in the incident log.

---

## 6. Post-incident

Within 30 days of resolution:

- Write a one-page post-mortem in the incident log: timeline, root cause, fix shipped, gap that allowed it
- Open a tracking issue for any structural fix (access-control audit, secret rotation policy, monitoring addition)
- Update this runbook if anything was unclear during the incident
- If the issue revealed an admin-side problem, log to the admin audit log for accountability

The regulator may request follow-up information months later. Keep the incident log indefinitely or until the case is closed in writing — whichever is later.

---

## 7. Detection signals to add (deferred until past beta)

Currently no automated signals. Detection is best-effort manual: occasional review of {{LOGS_LOCATION}}, error reporting, and source-control secret-scanning alerts.

When user count grows past beta, add at minimum:

- Failed-auth spike alarm
- Mass-export detector (rate-limit + alert on data-export endpoint per hour)
- Storage egress anomaly alarm
- Source-control secret-scanning enabled
- Quarterly review of admin audit log for unfamiliar actions

